Theresa May is setting out the details of a series of compromises designed to try and win the support of Labour MPs for her Brexit plan. The cabinet earlier agreed the idea of a temporary customs relationship until the next general election, and measures on the environment and workers’ rights. These will be included in the Withdrawal Agreement Bill, to be put to a vote in the Commons in early June. The SNP and some Tory Brexiteers have already said they will vote against. The PM briefed MPs and ministers on the contents of the speech – entitled “A new Brexit deal – seeking common ground in Parliament” – beforehand. UNITED KINGDOM: Brexit must not be frustrated, May vows United Kingdom: Brexit: MPs debate Theresa May’s next steps United Kingdom: May asks MPs for ‘honourable compromise’ on Brexit Dear Esteemed reader, As part of our drive to keep improving the content of our newspaper, we are conducting a readership survey to enable us serve you better. Kindly take two minutes of your time to fill in this questionnaire. Thank you for your time. Click here to begin